      <p>If you purchase 100 shares of Johnson &amp; Johnson, you become a part-owner. As they sell medical devices and pharmaceuticals globally, a fraction of those profits is directed to you every three months. That is the core of <a href="/what-is-a-dividend-stock">what is a dividend stock</a>.</p>

      <h2>Step-by-Step: Building a Dividend Portfolio</h2>

      <p>Transitioning from understanding the theory to actually generating <a href="/what-is-dividend-income">what is dividend income</a> requires a structured approach. Here is how you can start building your portfolio.</p>

      <h3>Step 1: Choose Your Account Wisely</h3>
      <p>Taxes matter. In a standard brokerage account, you will be taxed on the dividends you receive each year, even if you reinvest them. Depending on your tax bracket, qualified dividends are taxed favorably (often at 0%, 15%, or 20%), but it still creates a drag on your compounding. If possible, utilizing tax-advantaged accounts like a Roth IRA (in the US) or a TFSA (in Canada) allows your dividends to compound completely tax-free.</p>

      <h3>Step 2: Focus on Quality Over Yield</h3>
      <p>A common beginner mistake is chasing the highest yield possible. If a stock yields 12%, there is usually a reason—the market expects the dividend to be cut, or the business is in severe decline. Instead, look for companies with a history of consistent dividend <em>growth</em>. A company paying a 3% yield that increases its payout by 8% every year will often outperform a stagnant 7% yielder over a decade.</p>

      <h3>Step 3: Analyze the Payout Ratio</h3>
      <p>The payout ratio tells you what percentage of a company's earnings is being paid out as dividends. If a company earns $10 per share and pays $5 in dividends, the payout ratio is 50%. This is healthy; it leaves the company with plenty of cash to reinvest or weather a recession. If the payout ratio is 95% (or over 100%), the dividend is in danger of being cut.</p>

      <h3>Step 4: Turn on DRIP</h3>
      <p>DRIP stands for Dividend Reinvestment Plan. When you enable this feature with your broker, every cash dividend you receive is automatically used to purchase more shares (often fractional shares) of the underlying stock. More shares mean higher future dividend payments, which buy even more shares. This creates a powerful snowball effect over time.</p>

