            <p>You can start dividend investing with as little as a few dollars, thanks to fractional shares offered by many modern brokerages. However, to generate substantial income, a larger capital base is required.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Are dividend stocks safe?</summary>
          <div class="faq-content">
            <p>While dividend stocks from established, blue-chip companies are generally considered less volatile than growth stocks, they still carry market risk. A high dividend yield can sometimes be a warning sign of a struggling company.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Do I have to pay taxes on dividends?</summary>
          <div class="faq-content">
            <p>Yes, unless the investments are held in a tax-advantaged account like a Roth IRA or TFSA. In taxable accounts, dividends are typically taxed as either ordinary income or at the lower qualified dividend rate, depending on the holding period and the type of company.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What is a good dividend yield?</summary>
          <div class="faq-content">
            <p>A 'good' dividend yield typically ranges between 2% and 6%. Yields above this range may indicate higher risk, as the market could be pricing in a potential dividend cut. It's crucial to evaluate the payout ratio alongside the yield.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
    function formatCurrency(num) {
      return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
        style: 'currency',
        currency: 'USD',
        minimumFractionDigits: 0,
        maximumFractionDigits: 0
      }).format(num);
    }

    function initCalculator() {
      const initialInvestmentInput = document.getElementById('initialInvestment');
      const annualContributionInput = document.getElementById('annualContribution');
      const dividendYieldInput = document.getElementById('dividendYield');
      const yearsInput = document.getElementById('years');

      const projectedIncomeEl = document.getElementById('projectedIncome');
      const projectedValueEl = document.getElementById('projectedValue');
      const displayYearsEl = document.getElementById('displayYears');

      if (!initialInvestmentInput) return;

      function calculate() {
        const initial = parseFloat(initialInvestmentInput.value) || 0;
        const annualContrib = parseFloat(annualContributionInput.value) || 0;
        const yieldPct = (parseFloat(dividendYieldInput.value) || 0) / 100;
        const years = parseInt(yearsInput.value) || 0;

        let balance = initial;

        // Simple annual compounding model (assuming static stock price and static yield for illustration)
        // A more complex model would include dividend growth and capital appreciation.
        for (let i = 0; i < years; i++) {
          let dividendIncome = balance * yieldPct;
          balance += dividendIncome; // DRIP
          balance += annualContrib;
        }

        const finalIncome = balance * yieldPct;

        projectedIncomeEl.textContent = formatCurrency(finalIncome);
        projectedValueEl.textContent = formatCurrency(balance);
        displayYearsEl.textContent = years.toString();
      }

      // Add event listeners for real-time calculation
      [initialInvestmentInput, annualContributionInput, dividendYieldInput, yearsInput].forEach(input => {
        input.addEventListener('input', calculate);
      });

      // Initial calculation
      calculate();
    }

    // Support Astro View Transitions
    document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initCalculator);

    // Fallback for direct loads without view transitions
    if (document.readyState === 'loading') {
      document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initCalculator);
    } else {
      initCalculator();
    }
  </script>
</SiteLayout>
